Three data periods are used. Each serves a distinct purpose. All windows end on today's date.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
STEP 1 — ADF TEST  |  Data period: PAST 5 YEARS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Stationary means: constant mean; constant variance; doesn't wander indefinitely.

Run ADF twice — once for stock A and once for stock B — on the past 5 years of price data.
Interpretation: p < 0.05 = stationary; p > 0.05 = non-stationary.
If non-stationary: give it a check mark ✓ (this is required for cointegration).
If stationary: give it a question mark ? (unexpected for raw prices).

Display as a compact banner, NOT a full metrics table:
  - Both non-stationary (normal): show a single green success banner summarising both p-values.
  - Any series stationary (unusual): show an amber warning alert naming the stationary ticker and
    its p-value. Then show an info message for the non-stationary one. Alert the user that
    cointegration results may not be reliable.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
STEP 2 — ENGLE-GRANGER SPREAD CHARTS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Run Engle-Granger in BOTH directions, for TWO separate data periods: 5 years and 2 years.
This produces four spread charts in total.

For each direction and each data period:
   1) Regress A on B (or B on A): compute α (intercept) and β (hedge ratio)
   2) Compute residuals: ϵ = A − (α + β·B)
   3) Run ADF on residuals
   Interpretation: p < 0.05 = cointegrated (spread is stationary); p > 0.05 = not cointegrated

Primary direction per window = the direction (A→B or B→A) with the lower p-value.
The primary direction is determined independently for each data period — it may differ between
the 5-year and 2-year windows.

Chart order on dashboard:
   [Past 5 Years heading]
   Chart 1: ★ Primary direction  —  Spread (5yr): TICKER_A→TICKER_B  [start → end]
   Chart 2:   Reverse direction  —  Spread (5yr): TICKER_B→TICKER_A  [start → end]
   --- separator ---
   [Past 2 Years heading]
   Chart 3: ★ Primary direction  —  Spread (2yr): TICKER_A→TICKER_B  [start → end]
   Chart 4:   Reverse direction  —  Spread (2yr): TICKER_B→TICKER_A  [start → end]

Each chart shows:
   - Spread (residuals) over time with ±1σ bands and mean line
   - α (intercept), β (hedge ratio)
   - ADF test statistic, p-value, critical values (1% / 5% / 10%)
   - Verdict: Cointegrated ✓ or Not cointegrated ✗

The data period must be stated explicitly in each chart title (5yr or 2yr) along with the
exact date range (e.g. "Jun 2021 → Jun 2026").


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
STEP 3 — QUARTERLY P-VALUES  |  Data period: PAST 1 YEAR
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The past 1 year of daily price data is divided into 4 equal quarterly windows:
  Q1 = oldest quarter, Q2, Q3, Q4 = most recent quarter (~63 trading days each).

For each quarter, run Engle-Granger in BOTH directions and display BOTH p-values explicitly,
labelled with which ticker is regressed on which:

   ★ TICKER_A regressed on TICKER_B  →  p-value
     TICKER_B regressed on TICKER_A  →  p-value

★ marks the primary direction (the lower p-value). The primary drives the pass/fail verdict.
Pass condition per quarter: primary p-value < 0.05.

Output: 4 quarter cards side by side (Q1 = oldest, Q4 = most recent):
   Q1: date range | both direction p-values (labelled) | Cointegrated ✓ or Not cointegrated ✗
   Q2: same structure
   Q3: same structure
   Q4: same structure

Below the cards:
   "X/4 quarters passed" summary
   Final PASS banner (all 4 pass) or FAIL banner (any quarter fails)

The pair passes the full cointegration test only if ALL FOUR quarters pass (4/4).
Report how many quarters passed even when the overall verdict is FAIL.
